00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:35.000
and we'll use Shiny to make a much friendlier experience on top of this.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:38.000
So what is Shiny?

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:43.000
Shiny is a framework for making interactive web apps in pure Python.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.000
You do not need to know HTML, CSS, or JavaScript.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:51.000
If you don't want to, just pure Python, you're already halfway there

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.000
if you know how to code in Python.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:56.000
But if you do know HTML, CSS, and JavaScript,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:01.000
you can absolutely use them to enhance Shiny by customizing it and extending it,

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.000
which is something that I spent a lot of time doing this week,

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:08.000
and I can't wait to show you the results in a few moments here.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:13.000
Shiny is specifically designed for data-related applications.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:18.000
There's a lot of visualization built in that it works with Matplotlib and Plotly

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.000
and is designed to work with data frames.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
So you can use it for a lot of different things,

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:28.000
but it is especially well-suited for data-related applications.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:32.000
The heart of Shiny is a reactive programming model.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:36.000
If you have not heard that term before, you don't have to worry about it right now

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:40.000
except to know that this approach is really good at making your apps efficient

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:46.000
because only a minimum amount of code needs to run every time you interact with your app

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:50.000
in order to get your outputs to be correct.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:55.000
And it's also a very good programming paradigm

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:02.000
for avoiding the kinds of bugs that are usually pretty common in UI programming.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:08.000
It is an open-sourced framework, MIT-licensed,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:11.000
and after you've written your Shiny app, you can either run them locally

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:16.000
or you can deploy them in a variety of ways in the cloud or on-prem.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.000
We have a number of free and paid cloud options

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:24.000
as well as open-source and enterprise on-prem options,

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:30.000
and all that is described in the Shiny for Python documentation I'll link to at the end.

